{"title_page": "Lithops olivacea", "text_new": "{{Speciesbox\n| name = Lithops olivacea\n| image = Lithops olivacea - RSA 5.jpg\n| image_alt = \n| image_caption = \n| genus = Lithops\n| species = olivacea\n| authority = L.Bolus\n}}\n[[File:Lithops olivacea IB 2.jpg|alt=|thumb|''Lithops olivacea'']]\n\n''Lithops olivacea'' is a species of the genus ''[[Lithops]]'' under the family [[Aizoaceae]]. The name ''olivacea'' refers to the Latin word for olive (''oliva'') combined with the suffix ''-cea,'' meaning \"of the likeness,\" producing the idea of \"olive likeness.\" ''Lithops olivacea'' grow primarily in the [[Bushmanland (South West Africa)|Bushmandland]] of South Africa. They grow most abundantly in the regions of [[Aggeneys]], [[Pofadder, Northern Cape|Pofadder]], and Namies. <ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://pza.sanbi.org/lithops-olivacea|title=Lithops olivacea {{!}} PlantZAfrica|website=pza.sanbi.org|access-date=2019-03-13}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.llifle.com/Encyclopedia/SUCCULENTS/Family/Aizoaceae/13102/Lithops_olivacea|title=Lithops olivacea|website=www.llifle.com|access-date=2019-03-13}}</ref> ''L. olivacea'' also received the [[Royal Horticultural Society|Royal Horticultural Society's]] [[Award of Garden Merit]] for being \"excellent for ordinary use in appropriate conditions, available to buy, of good constitution, essentially stable in form & colour, [and] reasonably resistant to pests & diseases.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rhs.org.uk/Plants/10370/i-Lithops-olivacea-i/Details|title=RHS - Lithops oviacea|website=Royal Horticultural Society}}</ref>\n\n==Description==\nThe plant consists of bulbous leaves growing in pairs. Flowers will emerge from between the two leaves and sprout vertically. The leaves draw down into a small [[taproot]] which also grows [[adventitious root]]s when able. The flowers are yellow in color, and have a white center.<ref name=\":0\" /> O''livacea'' usually tends to grow near large deposits and formations of [[quartz]] for reasons of [[Camouflage|adapted camouflage]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://altmanplants.com/mimicry-succulent-plants/|title=Mimicry plants: succulent masters of disguise|date=2017-09-29|website=Altman Plants|language=en-US|access-date=2019-03-13}}</ref> Variety in the species allows for colors to range from red, to green, to yellow, to brown or gray, depending on environment or genetic traits.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.llifle.com/Encyclopedia/SUCCULENTS/Family/Aizoaceae/13102/Lithops_olivacea|title=Lithops olivacea|website=www.llifle.com|access-date=2019-03-13}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q5977182}}\n\n\n[[Category:Lithops|olivaceea]]\n", "text_old": "{{Speciesbox\n| name = Lithops olivacea\n| image = Lithops olivacea - RSA 5.jpg\n| image_alt = \n| image_caption = \n| genus = Lithops\n| species = olivacea\n| authority = L.Bolus\n}}\n[[File:Lithops olivacea IB 2.jpg|alt=|thumb|''Lithops olivacea'']]\n\n''Lithops olivacea'' is a species of the genus ''[[Lithops]]'' under the family [[Aizoaceae]]. The name ''olivacea'' refers to the Latin word for olive (''oliva'') combined with the suffix ''-cea,'' meaning \"of the likeness,\" producing the idea of \"olive likeness.\" ''Lithops olivacea'' grow primarily in the [[Bushmanland (South West Africa)|Bushmandland]] of South Africa. They grow most abundantly in the regions of [[Aggeneys]], [[Pofadder, Northern Cape|Pofadder]], and Namies. <ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://pza.sanbi.org/lithops-olivacea|title=Lithops olivacea {{!}} PlantZAfrica|website=pza.sanbi.org|access-date=2019-03-13}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.llifle.com/Encyclopedia/SUCCULENTS/Family/Aizoaceae/13102/Lithops_olivacea|title=Lithops olivacea|website=www.llifle.com|access-date=2019-03-13}}</ref> ''L. olivacea'' also received the [[Royal Horticultural Society|Royal Horticultural Society's]] [[Award of Garden Merit]] for being \"excellent for ordinary use in appropriate conditions, available to buy, of good constitution, essentially stable in form & colour, [and] reasonably resistant to pests & diseases.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rhs.org.uk/Plants/10370/i-Lithops-olivacea-i/Details|title=RHS - Lithops oviacea|website=Royal Horticultural Society}}</ref>\n\n==Description==\nThe plant consists of bulbous leaves growing in pairs. Flowers will emerge from between the two leaves and sprout vertically. The leaves draw down into a small [[taproot]] which also grows [[Adventitious Roots|adventitious roots]] when able. The flowers are yellow in color, and have a white center.<ref name=\":0\" /> O''livacea'' usually tends to grow near large deposits and formations of [[quartz]] for reasons of [[Camouflage|adapted camouflage]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://altmanplants.com/mimicry-succulent-plants/|title=Mimicry plants: succulent masters of disguise|date=2017-09-29|website=Altman Plants|language=en-US|access-date=2019-03-13}}</ref> Variety in the species allows for colors to range from red, to green, to yellow, to brown or gray, depending on environment or genetic traits.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.llifle.com/Encyclopedia/SUCCULENTS/Family/Aizoaceae/13102/Lithops_olivacea|title=Lithops olivacea|website=www.llifle.com|access-date=2019-03-13}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q5977182}}\n\n\n[[Category:Lithops|olivaceea]]\n", "name_user": "Hankwang", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eDescription:linkadventitious root, notAdventitious Roots", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lithops_olivacea"}
{"title_page": "1st Virginia Infantry", "text_new": "{{Infobox military unit\n|unit_name= 1st Regiment, Virginia Infantry\n|image= Flag of Virginia (1861).png\n|caption= Flag of Virginia, 1861\n|dates= May 1861 &ndash; Spring 1865\n|country= {{flag|Confederate States of America}}\n|allegiance={{flag|Virginia|1861}}\n|branch= {{army|CSA}}\n|type= \n|role= [[Infantry]]\n|nickname=\n|battles= [[First Battle of Bull Run]]<br/>[[Battle of Williamsburg]]<br/>[[Seven Days' Battles]]<br/>[[Second Battle of Bull Run]]<br/>[[Battle of Fredericksburg]]<br/>[[Battle of Gettysburg]]<br/>[[Battle of Cold Harbor]]<br/>[[Siege of Petersburg]]<br/>[[Battle of Five Forks]]<br/>[[Battle of Sailor's Creek]]\n|disbanded= April 1865\n<!-- Commanders -->\n|notable_commanders=\n}}\n[[File:Soldiers from Richmond Grays at execution of abolitionist John Brown in Charles Town, West Virginia LCCN2016650150.jpg|thumb|upright|Soldiers from Richmond Grays at execution of abolitionist John Brown in Charles Town, West Virginia 1859|alt=]]\n[[File:Theophilus Mann of Company G, 1st (Farinholt's) Virginia Infantry Battalion Reserves, with pistol and knife LCCN2012646162.jpg|thumb|right|Theophilus Mann of Company G, 1st (Farinholt's) Virginia Infantry Battalion Reserves]]\n\nThe '''1st Virginia Volunteer Infantry Regiment''' was an [[infantry]] [[regiment]] raised in the [[Virginia|Commonwealth of Virginia]] for service in the [[Confederate States Army]] during the [[American Civil War]]. It fought mostly with the [[Army of Northern Virginia]].\n\nThe 1st Virginia completed its organization at [[Richmond in the American Civil War|Richmond, Virginia]], in May, 1861. At the outbreak of the war it had ten companies, but in April three were detached. Thus the unit contained seven companies from Richmond and in mid-July a company from Washington, D.C. was added. Its first colonel, [[Patrick T. Moore]], was severely wounded on July 18, 1861, in the skirmish at [[Battle of Blackburn's Ford|Blackburn's Ford]], and Lt. Col. W.H. Fry commanded at the [[First Battle of Bull Run]] (First Manassas).\nThe companies (with original commanders) were:\n*Co. A (Richmond Grays): Capt. W.M. Elliott \u2013 Detached to [[Norfolk, Virginia]], during April, 1861 and assigned to the [[12th Virginia Infantry]] as Co. G, August 31, 1861.\n*Co. B (Richmond City Guard): Capt. R. Harrison \u2013 Captain J.K. Lee was killed at Blackburn's Ford on July 18, 1861.\n*Co. C (Montgomery Guard): Capt. J. Dooley\n*Co. D (Old Dominion Guard): Capt. J. Griswold\n*Co. E (1st) (Richmond Light Infantry Blues): Capt. O.J. Wise \u2013 Sent to [[Fredericksburg, Virginia]] and later assigned to the [[46th Virginia Infantry]], prior to the [[Battle of First Manassas]].\n*Co. E (2nd) (Washington Volunteers): Capt. C.K. Sherman \u2013 Temporarily attached to the regiment during the middle of July and transferred to the [[7th Virginia Infantry]] as Company F in April 1862.\n*Co. F (1st) (Cary's Company): Capt. R.M. Cary \u2013 Sent to Fredericksburg and assigned to the [[21st Virginia Infantry]], under the command of Capt. R.H. Cunningham, Jr., prior to [[First Manassas]].\n*Co. F (2nd) (Beauregard Rifles): Capt. F.B. Schaeffer \u2013 Served in a provisional battalion (Schaeffer's Battalion) during First Bull Run and was subsequently assigned to the regiment on July 23, 1861. The company was relieved from duty on September 7 and redesignated as Company C, 1st Regiment Virginia Artillery. On November 13, 1861, the company was mustered out of service. \n*Co. G (Gordan's Company): Capt. W.H. Gordan\n*Co. H (1st) (Howitzer Battery): Capt [[George W. Randolph|G.W. Randolph]] \u2013 In early May, the company left the regiment and was expanded into a battalion of three companies under then-Maj. G. W. Randolph.\n*Co. H (2nd) (Richmond Greys, Company B): Capt. F.J. Boggs\n*Co. I (Taylor's' Company): Capt. W.O. Taylor\n*Co. K (Virginia Rifles, at one time German Rifles): Capt. F. Miller \u2013 Disbanded when the regiment was reorganised in April 1862.\n*Fayette Artillery: Capt. H.C. Cabell \u2013 Detached and assigned to [[John B. Magruder|John Magruder's]] command on the [[Virginia Peninsula]].\n*Floyd Guard: Capt. G.W. Chambers \u2013 Assigned as Co. K, [[2nd Virginia Infantry]], prior to June 30, 1861.\n*Band: Capt. J.B. Smith \u2013 Mustered in as Co. I and detached to form the a 13 piece regimental band.\n*Drum Corps: Drum Major C.R.M. Pohle \u2013 14 drummers including the drummer on duty with the Richmond Greys in Norfolk. The Drum Corps was mustered in as a body.\n\nIt fought at the [[Battle of First Bull Run]] (First Manassas) in a brigade under [[James Longstreet]] and in August totaled 570 men. During April, 1862, when the regiment was reorganized, it contained only six companies. The 1st Virginia Infantry was assigned to [[A.P. Hill|A. P. Hill's]], [[James L. Kemper|Kemper's]], and [[William R. Terry|W. R. Terry's]] Brigade, Army of Northern Virginia. It was active from the [[Battle of Williamsburg]] to the [[Battle of Gettysburg]], except when it was with Longstreet at the [[Siege of Suffolk]], Virginia. Later the unit was involved in the capture of Plymouth, the conflicts at [[Bermuda Hundred Campaign|Drewry's Bluff]] and [[Battle of Cold Harbor|Cold Harbor]], the [[Siege of Petersburg]] south and north of the [[James River]], and the [[Appomattox Campaign]]. This regiment lost twenty-two percent of the 140 engaged at the [[Battle of Second Bull Run]] (Second Manassas), had 9 wounded at the [[Battle of Fredericksburg]], and had more than half of the 209 at Gettysburg disabled. Its casualties were 12 killed and 25 wounded at Drewry's Bluff, 1 killed and 77 wounded at the [[Battle of Five Forks]], and 40 captured at the [[Battle of Sayler's Creek]]. Only 17 surrendered at [[Battle of Appomattox Court House|Appomattox]] on April 9, 1865.\n\nThe field officers were Colonels [[Patrick T. Moore]], Franklin G. Skinner, and [[Lewis B. Williams Jr.|Lewis B. Williams, Jr]]; Lieutenant Colonels William H. Fry and Frank H. Langley; and Majors John Dooley, William P. Mumford, George F. Norton, and William H. Palmer.\n\n==See also==\n{{portal|American Civil War}}\n*[[List of Virginia Civil War units]]\n\n==References==\n<references />\n*{{USGovernment|sourceURL=[http://www.civilwar.nps.gov/cwss/regiments.cfm Civil War Soldiers and Sailors System], ''National Park Service}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Internet Archive|14246794.3326.emory.edu|War history of the old First Virginia Infantry Regiment, Army of Northern Virginia / by Charles T. Loehr (1884)}}\n* {{Internet Archive|05382282.3420.emory.edu|Record of the Richmond city and Henrico Co., Virginia troops, Confederate States Army (1879)}}\n* Curran, Robert Emmett ''[http://utpress.org/title/john-dooleys-civil-war/ John Dooley's Civil War An Irish American's Journey in the First Virginia Infantry Regiment]'' University of Tennessee Press, 2011.\n\n[[Category:Virginia Civil War regiments]]\n[[Category:1861 establishments in Virginia]]\n[[Category:Military units and formations established in 1861]]\n[[Category:1865 disestablishments in Virginia]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox military unit\n|unit_name= 1st Regiment, Virginia Infantry\n|image= Flag of Virginia (1861).png\n|caption= Flag of Virginia, 1861\n|dates= May 1861 &ndash; Spring 1865\n|country= {{flag|Confederate States of America}}\n|allegiance={{flag|Virginia|1861}}\n|branch= {{army|CSA}}\n|type= \n|role= [[Infantry]]\n|nickname=\n|battles= [[First Battle of Bull Run]]<br/>[[Battle of Williamsburg]]<br/>[[Seven Days' Battles]]<br/>[[Second Battle of Bull Run]]<br/>[[Battle of Fredericksburg]]<br/>[[Battle of Gettysburg]]<br/>[[Battle of Cold Harbor]]<br/>[[Siege of Petersburg]]<br/>[[Battle of Five Forks]]<br/>[[Battle of Sailor's Creek]]\n|disbanded= April 1865\n<!-- Commanders -->\n|notable_commanders=\n}}\n\n[[File:Soldiers from Richmond Grays at execution of abolitionist John Brown in Charles Town, West Virginia LCCN2016650150.jpg|thumb|upright|Soldiers from Richmond Grays at execution of abolitionist John Brown in Charles Town, West Virginia 1859|alt=]]\n\n[[File:Theophilus Mann of Company G, 1st (Farinholt's) Virginia Infantry Battalion Reserves, with pistol and knife LCCN2012646162.jpg|thumb|right|Theophilus Mann of Company G, 1st (Farinholt's) Virginia Infantry Battalion Reserves]]\n\nThe '''1st Virginia Volunteer Infantry Regiment''' was an [[infantry]] [[regiment]] raised in the [[Virginia|Commonwealth of Virginia]] for service in the [[Confederate States Army]] during the [[American Civil War]]. It fought mostly with the [[Army of Northern Virginia]].\n\n\nThe 1st Virginia completed its organization at [[Richmond in the American Civil War|Richmond, Virginia]], in May, 1861. At the outbreak of the war it had ten companies, but in April three were detached. Thus the unit contained seven companies from Richmond and in mid-July a company from Washington, D.C. was added. Its first colonel, [[Patrick T. Moore]], was severely wounded on July 18, 1861, in the skirmish at [[Battle of Blackburn's Ford|Blackburn's Ford]], and Lt. Col. W.H. Fry commanded at the [[First Battle of Bull Run]] (First Manassas).\nThe companies (with original commanders) were:\n*Co. A (Richmond Grays): Capt. W.M. Elliott \u2013 Detached to [[Norfolk, Virginia]], during April, 1861 and assigned to the [[12th Virginia Infantry]] as Co. G, August 31, 1861.\n*Co. B (Richmond City Guard): Capt. R. Harrison \u2013 Captain J.K. Lee was killed at Blackburn's Ford on July 18, 1861.\n*Co. C (Montgomery Guard): Capt. J. Dooley\n*Co. D (Old Dominion Guard): Capt. J. Griswold\n*Co. E (1st) (Richmond Light Infantry Blues): Capt. O.J. Wise \u2013 Sent to [[Fredericksburg, Virginia]] and later assigned to the [[46th Virginia Infantry]], prior to the [[Battle of First Manassas]].\n*Co. E (2nd) (Washington Volunteers): Capt. C.K. Sherman \u2013 Temporarily attached to the regiment during the middle of July and transferred to the [[7th Virginia Infantry]] as Company F in April 1862.\n*Co. F (1st) (Cary's Company): Capt. R.M. Cary \u2013 Sent to Fredericksburg and assigned to the [[21st Virginia Infantry]], under the command of Capt. R.H. Cunningham, Jr., prior to [[First Manassas]].\n*Co. F (2nd) (Beauregard Rifles): Capt. F.B. Schaeffer \u2013 Served in a provisional battalion (Schaeffer's Battalion) during First Bull Run and was subsequently assigned to the regiment on July 23, 1861. The company was relieved from duty on September 7 and redesignated as Company C, 1st Regiment Virginia Artillery. On November 13, 1861, the company was mustered out of service. \n*Co. G (Gordan's Company): Capt. W.H. Gordan\n*Co. H (1st) (Howitzer Battery): Capt [[George W. Randolph|G.W. Randolph]] \u2013 In early May, the company left the regiment and was expanded into a battalion of three companies under then-Maj. G. W. Randolph.\n*Co. H (2nd) (Richmond Greys, Company B): Capt. F.J. Boggs\n*Co. I (Taylor's' Company): Capt. W.O. Taylor\n*Co. K (Virginia Rifles, at one time German Rifles): Capt. F. Miller \u2013 Disbanded when the regiment was reorganised in April 1862.\n*Fayette Artillery: Capt. H.C. Cabell \u2013 Detached and assigned to [[John B. Magruder|John Magruder's]] command on the [[Virginia Peninsula]].\n*Floyd Guard: Capt. G.W. Chambers \u2013 Assigned as Co. K, [[2nd Virginia Infantry]], prior to June 30, 1861.\n*Band: Capt. J.B. Smith \u2013 Mustered in as Co. I and detached to form the a 13 piece regimental band.\n*Drum Corps: Drum Major C.R.M. Pohle \u2013 14 drummers including the drummer on duty with the Richmond Greys in Norfolk. The Drum Corps was mustered in as a body.\n\nIt fought at the Battle of First Bull Run (First Manassas) in a brigade under [[James Longstreet]] and in August totaled 570 men. During April, 1862, when the regiment was reorganized, it contained only six companies. The 1st Virginia Infantry was assigned to [[A.P. Hill|A. P. Hill's]], [[James L. Kemper|Kemper's]], and [[William R. Terry|W. R. Terry's]] Brigade, Army of Northern Virginia. It was active from the [[Battle of Williamsburg]] to the [[Battle of Gettysburg]] except when it was with Longstreet at the [[Siege of Suffolk]], Virginia. Later the unit was involved in the capture of Plymouth, the conflicts at [[Bermuda Hundred Campaign|Drewry's Bluff]] and [[Battle of Cold Harbor|Cold Harbor]], the [[Siege of Petersburg]] south and north of the [[James River]], and the [[Appomattox Campaign]]. This regiment lost twenty-two percent of the 140 engaged at the [[Battle of Second Bull Run]] (Second Manassas), had 9 wounded at the [[Battle of Fredericksburg]], and had more than half of the 209 at Gettysburg disabled. Its casualties were 12 killed and 25 wounded at Drewry's Bluff, 1 killed and 77 wounded at the [[Battle of Five Forks]], and 40 captured at the [[Battle of Sayler's Creek]]. Only 17 surrendered at [[Battle of Appomattox Court House|Appomattox]] on April 9, 1865.\n\nThe field officers were Colonels [[Patrick T. Moore]], Franklin G. Skinner, and [[Lewis B. Williams Jr.|Lewis B. Williams, Jr]]; Lieutenant Colonels William H. Fry and Frank H. Langley; and Majors John Dooley, William P. Mumford, George F. Norton, and William H. Palmer.\n\n==See also==\n{{portal|American Civil War}}\n*[[List of Virginia Civil War units]]\n\n==References==\n<references />\n*{{USGovernment|sourceURL=[http://www.civilwar.nps.gov/cwss/regiments.cfm Civil War Soldiers and Sailors System], ''National Park Service}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Internet Archive|14246794.3326.emory.edu|War history of the old First Virginia Infantry Regiment, Army of Northern Virginia / by Charles T. Loehr (1884)}}\n* {{Internet Archive|05382282.3420.emory.edu|Record of the Richmond city and Henrico Co., Virginia troops, Confederate States Army (1879)}}\n* Curran, Robert Emmett ''[http://utpress.org/title/john-dooleys-civil-war/ John Dooley's Civil War An Irish American's Journey in the First Virginia Infantry Regiment]'' University of Tennessee Press, 2011.\n\n[[Category:Virginia Civil War regiments]]\n[[Category:1861 establishments in Virginia]]\n[[Category:Military units and formations established in 1861]]\n[[Category:1865 disestablishments in Virginia]]\n", "name_user": "Deisenbe", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:Spelling/grammar/punctuation/typographical correction", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1st_Virginia_Infantry"}
{"title_page": "Netherlands national under-19 basketball team", "text_new": "{{Infobox national basketball team\n| country            = Netherlands \n| logo               = Flag of Netherlands.svg\n| logo_width         = 130px \n| nickname           = Orange Lions\n| fiba_zone          = FIBA Europe\n| national_fed       = [[Basketball Nederland]]\n| coach              = [[Paul Vervaeck]]\n| wc_championship    = [[FIBA Under-19 Basketball World Cup|Under-19 World Cup]]\n| wc_appearances     = None \n| wc_medals          = \n| zone_championship  = [[FIBA U18 European Championship|U18 European Championship]]\n| zone_appearances   = 5\n| zone_medals        = None\n| zone_championship2 = [[FIBA Europe Under-18 Championship Division B|U18 European Championship Division B]]\n| zone_appearances2  = 14\n| zone_medals2       = {{Eur1}} ''Gold:'' ([[2018 FIBA Europe Under-18 Championship Division B|2018]])\n| h_body             = FF5800\n| h_title            = Home\n| h_pattern_b        = _black_nzfc_shoulders\n| h_shorts           = FF5800\n| h_pattern_s        = \n| a_title            = Away\n| a_body             = FFFFFF\n| a_pattern_b        =  _black_nzfc_shoulders\n| a_shorts           = FFFFFF\n| a_pattern_s        = \n}}\n\nThe '''Netherlands national under-18 and under-19 basketball team''' is the national junior representative for the [[Netherlands]] in international under-18 and under-19 [[basketball]] tournaments.<ref>{{cite web|title=Netherlands (U18-U19)|url=https://www.eurobasket.com/Holland/basketball-National-Team.asp?Age=18|accessdate=6 November 2019}}</ref> They are governed by [[Basketball Nederland]]. The team competes at the [[FIBA U18 European Championship]], with the opportunity to qualify for the [[FIBA Under-19 Basketball World Cup|FIBA Under-19 World Cup]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Netherlands at the 2016 FIBA U18 European Championship Division B|url=https://www.fiba.basketball/europe/u18b/2016/Netherlands|accessdate=7 August 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Netherlands at the 2017 FIBA U18 European Championship Division B|url=https://www.fiba.basketball/europe/u18b/2017/Netherlands|accessdate=6 August 2017}}</ref>  The current coach is [[Paul Vervaeck]].\n\nIn 2018, the team won its first medal when it won gold at the [[2018 FIBA U18 European Championship Division B]] tournament.<ref name=\"FIBA.basketball 2018\">{{cite web | title=Netherlands celebrate historic title in Skopje | website=FIBA.basketball | date= | url=http://www.fiba.basketball/europe/u18b/2018/news/netherlands-celebrate-historic-title-in-skopje | access-date=5 August 2018}}</ref> Following their victory, the Netherlands were promoted to Division A.\n\n==Competitive record==\n{{col-begin|width=auto}}\n{{col-break}}\n===U18 European Championship===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"   \n|-\n!Year\n!width=\"100\"|Position\n|- \n|{{flagicon|Italy}} [[1964 FIBA Europe Under-18 Championship|1964]]||rowspan=5|''Did not participate''\n|- \n|{{flagicon|Italy}} [[1966 FIBA Europe Under-18 Championship|1966]]\n|- \n|{{flagicon|Spain|1945}} [[1968 FIBA Europe Under-18 Championship|1968]]\n|- \n|{{flagicon|Greece}} [[1970 FIBA Europe Under-18 Championship|1970]]\n|- \n|{{flagicon|Yugoslavia}} [[1972 FIBA Europe Under-18 Championship|1972]]\n|- \n|{{flagicon|France}} [[1974 FIBA Europe Under-18 Championship|1974]]||12th\n|-\n|{{flagicon|Spain|1945}} [[1976 FIBA Europe Under-18 Championship|1976]]||rowspan=5|''Did not participate''\n|- \n|{{flagicon|Italy}} [[1978 FIBA Europe Under-18 Championship|1978]]\n|- \n|{{flagicon|Yugoslavia}} [[1980 FIBA Europe Under-18 Championship|1980]]\n|- \n|{{flagicon|Bulgaria|1971}} [[1982 FIBA Europe Under-18 Championship|1982]]\n|- \n|{{flagicon|Sweden}} [[1984 FIBA Europe Under-18 Championship|1984]]\n|- \n|{{flagicon|Austria}} [[1986 FIBA Europe Under-18 Championship|1986]]||11th\n|- \n|{{flagicon|Yugoslavia}} [[1988 FIBA Europe Under-18 Championship|1988]]||12th\n|- \n|{{flagicon|Netherlands}} [[1990 FIB